description:
## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
complexity
## Location
src/context.rs:37-82 (neutralize_reminder_delimiters + replace_case_insensitive)
## Violation
```rust
let mut out = content.to_string();
for delim in DELIMITERS {
    if out.to_ascii_lowercase().contains(delim) {
        out = replace_case_insensitive(&out, delim);
    }
}
```

`out.to_ascii_lowercase()` allocates a full copy of the string once per delimiter (4x). Then `replace_case_insensitive` itself allocates a second lowercase copy and a third output `String`. For a hook output of N bytes scanning K delimiters the algorithm runs O(N·K) with up to 9 full-string allocations even when no delimiter is present. The work is paid on EVERY hook invocation regardless of whether the hook produced anything dangerous.

The double-pass (`contains` + replace) also means a delimiter that appears in only one casing variant still triggers two lowercase allocations.
## Mandated refactor
Lowercase the haystack ONCE up front. Walk it linearly with a single state machine that recognizes any of the four delimiter prefixes, emitting either the original byte or the escaped form. Return early with `content.to_string()` (one allocation) when the linear scan finds no delimiter. A regex-based `regex::RegexSet` over the four patterns is also acceptable and benchmarks well under the current implementation.
